Speakers: David Steinberger, Chip Mosher, David Brothers, Kuo-Yu Liang

Description: The comics industry is changing, and the digital revolution is here. Join comiXology co-founders David Steinberger and John D. Roberts, along with comiXology’s Head of Content Chip Mosher and Kuo-Yu Liang, VP of International Business Development at Diamond Comics Distributors, as they discuss the future of digital comics, graphic novels, and manga in this can’t-miss panel. Moderated by comiXology’s David Brothers.



The panel started with a brief history of comiXology, which was founded in 2007 and bought by Amazon in 2014. The company has had over 200 million downloads of their app, and they are the top grossing non-game iPad app in the entire App Store in 2013. They also have over 75,000 comics available from over 125 publishers as well as 1,000s of independent creators from around the world. ComiXology also has a self-publishing portal called comiXology Submit.

ComiXology’s goal is to make “everyone on the face of the planet a comics fan”, and they are accomplishing this by making comic book store experience more user friendly and accessible. They have done this by reaching out to new audiences, such as women and international audiences. ComiXology’s CEO David Steinberger said that they have seen double digital growth in their demographics especially in the 17-26 and over 55 age ranges. ComiXology’s head of content Chip Mosher said that romance comics are their highest growing genre, and they are reaching out to romance novel fans about the comics. ComiXology also has found international success with their production of French bandes dessinées and manga with the latter being helped by their 2014 acquisition of Anime News Network.



The floor was opened to questions where the comiXology CEO and head of content were joined by Kuo-Yu Liang, VP of International Business Development at Diamond Comics Distributors and David Brothers, a Branding Manager at Image Comics. Most of the questions focused on the business side of digital comics, like Amazon’s role in comiXology, digital sale numbers, and the demographics of digital comics readers. Steinberger said that Amazon has helped comiXology with their search algorithm and recommendation features, but that comiXology still has some autonomy and is run out of New York unlike the main Amazon offices in Seattle. Chip Mosher was quiet about digital numbers, but said that the digital and direct market for comics feed off each other and that digital sales don’t cannibalize print sales. He also said that Mark Millar’s Starlight #1 selling 35,000 copies in print and 90,000 copies with digital and print sales combined. Mosher also said that digital sales numbers are steady and that the Submit portal is a good way to look at digital sale trends with Submit titles making up 20% of their Top 1000 sellers and 50% of their Top 100 sellers.



The panelists also discussed their favorite comiXology Submit titles with Steinberger enjoying the “great cartooning and comedy” of Katie Cook’s Gronk and the “colorful art and great storytelling” of Katie Longua’s Munchies. Mosher said he liked the “wonderful cartooning” of The Chairs by Matthew Bogart and Just Another Sheep by Mat Heagerty and JD Faith, which he compared to X-Men if they were hippies. Liang said he liked the art of Oh Joy Sex Toy by Erika Moen and Matthew Nolan, and Brothers praised Sacrifice, which is written by comiXology’s Sam Humphries with art by Dalton Rose.

The panel concluded with Brothers talking about how digital comics provide a space for diverse stories and voices, like Nilah Magruder’s M.F.K, which won the first ever Dwayne McDuffie Diversity in Comics Award and how digital helps him stay in touch with the American comics market as an expat living in Japan.



The panel was quite informative and gave attendees a look into the history and inner workings of comiXology as well as the digital comics market as a whole. It was definitely a must-see for people interested in the digital side of the comics industry.

Metro is in the process of seeking input from the public about how the agency’s budget should be structured to best meet the needs of the Los Angeles County region. Metro’s telephone town hall meetings will include a brief presentation by Metro CEO Phillip A. Washington and budget staff. There will be an opportunity for the public to ask questions and share their comments and recommendations. Metro is also seeking input from riders and stakeholders through an online survey at metro.net.

To participate in the telephone town hall meetings, the public can pre-register by visiting tthm.wufoo.com/forms/metro-telephone-town-hall-signup. Once registered, participants will receive a telephone call at the start of the meeting inviting them to join. The public can also join the meeting by dialing 888-400-1932 for English and 888-400-9342 for Spanish.

For more information about the telephone town hall meetings, visit metro.net.



The Los Angeles County Metropolitan Transportation Authority (Metro) will hold a public hearing on a draft $5.6-billion budget for Fiscal Year 2016-17 on Wednesday, May 18, at 1 p.m. The hearing will be in the 3rd Floor Board Room at Metro headquarters, One Gateway Plaza, Los Angeles, CA 90012, adjacent to Union Station.

The proposed budget represents a 1.4 percent decrease from FY 2015-16, reflecting completion of the purchase of new buses and rail cars. The budget includes $2.4 billion for transportation improvements and $1.8 billion for transit operations. The remaining $1.4 billion is allocated for multi-year capital projects, debt service and fund balances.

The budget includes funding for the opening of two major rail projects, the Expo Line extension to Santa Monica on May 20 and the Gold Line extension to Azusa that opened in March. It also provides $1.4 billion for new construction, including the Regional Connector, the Crenshaw/LAX Transit Project, the Purple Line Extension Phase 1, freeway improvements, new sound walls and pedestrian improvements, among others.

The budget also includes funding for the continuation of the successful Metro ExpressLanes on the I-10 and I-110 freeways and for the Freeway Service Patrol and other services that keep traffic moving.

Metro CEO Phillip A. Washington will present the budget to the Metro Board of Directors at their May meeting. A final budget for FY 2016-17 will be adopted at the Metro Board’s meeting in June.

The public can view the budget at metro.net.

I was sitting at my favorite table at the local coffee shop, sipping on my usual cappuccino and reading the newspaper when I noticed her. She was sitting at the table next to mine, her long brown hair cascading down her back as she sipped on her tea. She was beautiful, and I couldn’t help but stare.

I tried to focus on my newspaper, but I couldn’t stop thinking about her. I wanted to talk to her, but I didn’t know what to say. I was too shy to approach her, so I just sat there, admiring her from afar.

Finally, I mustered up the courage to say something. I cleared my throat and said, “Excuse me, I couldn’t help but notice you’re drinking tea. I’m more of a coffee person myself, but I’ve been wanting to try something new. Do you have any recommendations?”

She looked up from her cup and smiled. “Of course,” she said. “I’m a bit of a tea connoisseur, so I can definitely help you out. What kind of flavors do you like?”

We chatted for a while about different types of tea, and she recommended a few that she thought I would like. I was so engrossed in our conversation that I didn’t even notice the time passing.

Before I knew it, the coffee shop was closing for the night. We exchanged numbers and promised to meet up again soon. As I walked home, I couldn’t stop smiling. I had finally found someone who shared my love of hot beverages, and I couldn’t wait to see where our newfound friendship would take us.
